		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">For me, the fact that they are for the PC makes them completely uninteresting.</div><br />Let's consider another scenario: A homebrew game is developed with accurate emulators (nintendulator/nestopia) and occasionally tested successfully on an NES, but is it not available for purchase as an NES Game Pak, nor is the NES PowerPak in stock. Does the fact that the primary audience is emulator users make it as uninteresting as a pure-PC game?<br /><br />Would a GBA game be less interesting than an NES game?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Anyone can do anything with a PC.</div>
<br />Except have more than one player control a character. If shared-screen multiplayer on a PC is so easy, then why can't the major PC game developers figure it out? Why can't PC games other than Lego Star Wars and Serious Sam read more than one gamepad connected to a single PC?

		

